		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Return to Its Master: Can it be done?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.70)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3300'>Ryan "Shadow 13" French</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3300&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 8, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Some of us are just born to be bad.  I&#39;m one, I think.  When I play Star Wars, I like playing Hunt Down or Lightsaber Combat with at least four Darth Maul&#39;s.  If I ever took up Star Trek, I&#39;d play Khan trying to steal the Genesis Device for use on Earth.  So naturally, when I play Lord of the Rings, I play Nazgûl.  But I&#39;ve had a lot of trouble trying to pin down the right deck to play them in.  And no matter what version of Nazgûl I&#39;m playing, I wish I was playing Return to Its Master Nazgûl.  For those of you who aren&#39;t familiar with the card, let&#39;s take a look at it:<br />
<br />
  Return to Its Master<br />
Nazgûl Culture - Event - Twilight Cost: 0<br />
Respose: If the Ring-bearer wears The One Ring at the end of a skirmish phase, cancel all remaining assignments and assign a Nazgûl to skirmish the Ring-bearer; The One Ring&#39;s game text does not apply during this skirmish.<br />
<br />
What does this mean?  If Frodo tries to wear his jewelry, he gets smacked down by a ringwraith, that&#39;s what it means.  And chances are he ain&#39;t getting back up.  This article will explore the practical uses of the card, culminating in a decklist that best takes advantage of it.<br />
<br />
First of all, we have to make sure we have this event when we need it.  That means if we&#39;re serious, we&#39;ll play 4x Return to Its Master.  Simple enough.  Now comes the hard part.  How do we make Frodo wear the Ring?  There are only two Shadow cards that directly force the Ring-bearer to put on the Ring:<br />
<br />
  Saruman&#39;s Reach<br />
Isengard Culture - Event - Twilight Cost: 0<br />
Search. Maneuver: Exert an Uruk-hai to make the opponent choose to either exert 2 companions or make the Ring-bearer put on The One Ring until the regroup phase.<br />
<br />
  Resistance Becomes Unbearable<br />
Nazgûl Culture - Event - Twilight Cost: 1<br />
Maneuver: Exert a twilight Nazgûl to exert the Ring-bearer.  If the Ring-bearer is then exhausted, he puts on The One Ring until the regroup phase.<br />
<br />
We&#39;ll explore a deck with Saruman&#39;s Reach first, then come back to Resistance Becomes Unbearable later.  To make a Return to Its Master/Saruman&#39;s Reach deck, we basically have to exhaust every companion before the Ring-bearer is sure to wear the Ring.  Plus, we have to mix our Shadow deck with Nazgûl and Uruk-Hai so we can use both of our events.  So we&#39;ll put in 4x Saruman&#39;s Reach to make sure we get it at the same time we have Return.  To exhaust every companion, we&#39;ll add Wizard Storm x4, although it&#39;s doubtful that a wary opponent will try to move through it.  They might if we get ahead, or if we don&#39;t appear to have any minions in our hand (sneaky us...).  To play these conditions and events, we have to spot Uruk-Hai or White Hand minions.  Let&#39;s start with 4x Uruk Scout, who not only deploy our conditions but also let each other deploy for cheap and cancel Ranger events.  We&#39;ll also add 4x Uruk Shaman to keep them in top fighting condition.  And to make sure they really do damage when they fight, let&#39;s add 4x Savagery To Match Their Numbers.  We won&#39;t use Saruman&#39;s Ambition because Albert Dreary and other cards can discard that, and we can&#39;t use Bred for Battle because we exert our Uruks to deploy conditions.<br />
<br />
Already we have 19 cards lined up.  Now we need to pick the Nazgûl we&#39;re going to use to overwhelm the Ring-bearer once we play Return to Its Master.  And remember, a Nazgûl needs to survive the first skirmish before you can play this card.  Of course we can&#39;t use the new twilight Witch-King because his game text prevents Return from being played.  But we can use Úlairë Enquëa, Ringwraith in Twilight, who does nearly the same thing as the Witch-King.  With an un-exhausted Enquëa beating the Ring-bearer in a Return to Its Master skirmish, you cause two wounds automatically, three if Enquëa is damage +1 or you can spot 5 burdens, four wounds if both.  And without Isildur&#39;s Bane, four wounds kills poor Frodo since he can&#39;t use the Ring.  So 4x Twilight Úlairë Enquëa is a must.  To make sure he spots 5 burdens, we&#39;ll complement him with 2x The Twilight World.  However, Enquëa&#39;s very expensive, so let&#39;s add some stuff to keep his cost down: 2x Morgul Gates.  And to make sure we have the right places to put him, we&#39;ll bid to go second, our first three sites being East Road, Weathertop, and the Ford of Bruinen.  But that doesn&#39;t help us deploy all our Uruks...so we&#39;ll do something about twilight at the same time we help manage our decksize: we&#39;ll ad 4x Goblin Runner and 2x They Are Coming.  We&#39;ll also use the Shores of Nen Hithoel later on, plus Emyn Muil to make sure our last battle is a nasty one.  Since we&#39;d probably play Rangers on the Free Peoples side of this deck, we&#39;ll use Lothlórien Woods and Silverlode Banks as our other sites.<br />
<br />
So to make Return to Its Master work, you must have in your hand at the beginning of your Shadow phase: Return to Its Master, Úlairë Enquëa, Saruman&#39;s Reach, and an Uruk.  to play all that, you need 9 twilight assuming none of them are roaming.  This shouldn&#39;t be too hard at the later sites...but will Enquëa survive his first skirmish once your opponent knows what your plan is?  Because it&#39;s not easy to keep the secret of this combo.  And with 38 cards in our deck, we just don&#39;t have room to consider teching against strategies that will destroy our combo: strategies like Hobbit exertion healing, mad condition healing with Choice of Luthien + Shoulder to Shoulder, or just passing the Ring to Sam when Frodo gets smashed.  And don&#39;t forget the new Hobbit card, Fearing the Worst, which would make Saruman&#39;s Reach twilight cost +2.  All in all, this deck doesn&#39;t look like a winner.<br />
<br />
So let&#39;s go back to the drawing board.  We have 4x Return to Its Master, and we&#39;re staring at Resistance Becomes Unbearable.  Let&#39;s go with that; we&#39;ll put 4 in our deck.  So to use this, we need twilight Nazgûl up the yin-yang, but we still can&#39;t use the twilight Witch-King.  So we&#39;ll use 4x each of the other 3.  Úlairë Enquëa is an excellent choice because if we don&#39;t manage to make the Ring-bearer put on the Ring this turn, by winning skirmishes with Enquëa we can wound the Ring-bearer so he&#39;s more likely to wear the Ring next turn.  This also gives us ally destruction, thanks to Attëa.  We&#39;ll also use Moria Lake to make sure Frodo takes yet another exertion.<br />
<br />
So now we have 20 cards, and it looks like they just might do it alone.  But we&#39;ll help them out just a little more.  To make sure they all come out to play, we&#39;ll throw in 4x Morgul Gates, East Road, the Ford of Bruinen, and the Shores of Nen Hithoel, bidding to go second again.  And to make sure they fight twice as long, we&#39;ll use Weathertop, Emyn Muil, and 4x Úlairë Otsëa.  And to make sure that O Elbereth! Gilthoniel! doesn&#39;t spoil our fun by pulling the Ring off, we&#39;ll add 2x The Witch-King, Lord of Angmar and 2x Stricken Dumb.  That puts us right at 32 cards, just about perfect.  But there are still a few things we need to take care of.  Even though we could probably pull off this combo twice in one game, once for Frodo and once for Sam, we&#39;ll throw in a Helpless so we don&#39;t have to.  And to keep the burdens high for Enquëa, we&#39;ll add just 1x The Twilight World.  And we&#39;ll throw in a Black Breath, for exclusive use on the Ring-bearer, to make sure he can&#39;t stop us from making him wear the Ring whenever we want him to.  Now we&#39;re at 35 cards, which is just about perfect for a good Nazgûl deck if there&#39;s a good Free Peoples side backing it up with drawing and discarding mechanisms.<br />
<br />
This all-Nazgûl deck looks a lot more solid than the first deck we came up with.  All the parts of this deck work together well; the first deck was disjointed in requiring too much of each culture.  With this deck we know where we&#39;re going and exactly how to get there, and we could probably pull off a win without ever playing Return to Its Master because our Nazgûl are strong enough to consistently slow down the opposition.<br />
<br />
I won&#39;t go into a Free Peoples half-deck to combine with this one, although I&#39;ll say that a Ranger/Elf deck generally mixes well with Nazgûl.  With 34 cards in each deck, you&#39;ll probably want to include Gwemegil to drop extra cards from hand, and maybe Elrond or the new Gandalf for increased drawing.  So for our other sites we&#39;ll say Lothlórien Woods and Silverlode Banks.<br />
<br />
Here&#39;s the two half-decks we built during this article, starting with the Uruk/Nazgûl Combo deck:<br />
  Sites:<br />
East Road<br />
Weathertop<br />
Ford of Bruinen<br />
Hollin<br />
Bridge<br />
Lothlórien Woods<br />
Silverlode Banks<br />
Shores of Nen Hithoel<br />
Emyn Muil<br />
<br />
  Shadow(38):<br />
Return to Its Master x4<br />
Saruman&#39;s Reach x4<br />
Wizard Storm x4<br />
Uruk Scout x4<br />
Uruk Shaman x4<br />
Savagery To Match Their Numbers x4<br />
Úlairë Enquëa, Ringwraith in Twilight x4<br />
The Twilight World x2<br />
Morgul Gates x2<br />
Goblin Runner x4<br />
They Are Coming x2<br />
<br />
<br />
And here&#39;s the pure Nazgûl deck:<br />
  Sites:<br />
East Road<br />
Weathertop<br />
Ford of Bruinen<br />
Moria Lake<br />
Bridge<br />
Lothlórien Woods<br />
Silverlode Banks<br />
Shores of Nen Hithoel<br />
Emyn Muil<br />
<br />
  Shadow deck(35):<br />
Return to Its Master x4<br />
Resistance Becomes Unbearable x4<br />
Úlairë Enquëa, Ringwraith in Twilight x4<br />
Úlairë Attëa, The Easterling x4<br />
Úlairë Nelya, Ringwraith in Twilight x4<br />
Morgul Gates x4<br />
Úlairë Otsëa, Lieutenant of Morgul x4<br />
The Witch-King, Lord of Angmar x2<br />
Stricken Dumb x2<br />
Helpless<br />
The Twilight World<br />
Black Breath<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading my article.  I hope it has given you some insight into the strengths of this card, and tickled your imagination with the possibilities...<br />
<br />
<br />
Ryan French<br />
